{
  "doc_id": "9694",
  "text": "The accuracy and validity of this method were reported in previous studies, showing a good to excellent test-retest reliability. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] There are two different forms of MND: simple and complex MND. This classification is based on the number of dysfunctions present (before the onset of puberty) or on the type of dysfunction (after the onset of puberty). A simple MND is considered to be in the range of a \"normal\" neurological performance and is also described as \"minor neurological difference\". In contrast, the presence of a complex MND reflects a neurological dysfunction and, regarding developmental aspects, is strongly related to learning and behavioral disorders.",
